sec.p:
MTF represents the capability to transfer the input signal modulation at a given spatial frequency to its output, and can be used to evaluate the fundamental spatial resolution performance of an imaging system. The spatial resolution can be determined by the spatial frequency value when MTF = 0.2. The MTF curve was calculated by the slanted-edge method. First, a piece of aluminium (thickness: ~1 mm) with a sharp edge was placed on the scintillator, and its edge profile was derived from the resulting X-ray image. Then, the edge spread function (ESF) was derived from the edge profile, from which we could deduce the line spread function (LSF). Finally, the MTF values were defined by the Fourier transform of the LSF as follows:MTFν=FLSFx=FdESFxdx,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
